        <!-- 13. H2 Why C.A.Gs -->
        <h2 id="why" class={h2}>Why Buyers Who Choose the Grey Choose C.A.Gs</h2>
        <p class={p}>If the honest answer for you is the African Grey, the next question is where to get one — and that decision matters as much as the species. Here at C.A.Gs we raise Greys, not Eclectus, and everything about how we place a bird is built around the checks a careful buyer should insist on.</p>

        <figure class="m-0 my-6">
          <img src={trustPhoto} width="640" height="480" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="w-full rounded-2xl border border-stone-200" alt="Mark and Teri Benjamin with a hand-raised Congo African Grey at C.A.Gs in Midland, Texas" title="Why buyers choose C.A.Gs | C.A.Gs" />
          <figcaption class={figc}>Real people, real birds, real paperwork — a breeder you can verify.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3 class={h3}>Hand-Raised, DNA-Sexed and Documented</h3>
        <p class={p}>Every C.A.Gs Grey is hand-raised in our home in Midland, Texas, PCR DNA-sexed, examined by an avian vet, and sent home with CITES Appendix I documentation and a written health guarantee. You're not hoping the bird is healthy and legal — you're holding the paperwork that proves it.</p>

        <h3 class={h3}>Lifetime Breeder Support and Nationwide Shipping</h3>
        <p class={p}>Because a Grey can share 40–60 years of your life, the relationship shouldn't end at the airport. We answer questions for the life of the bird and ship nationwide on IATA-compliant flights.</p>
        <h4 class={h4}>What Lifetime Support Actually Covers</h4>
        <p class={p}>It means you have a number to call for the plucking scare in year three and the diet question in year eight — the everyday milestones of Grey ownership — with the people who raised your bird on the other end.</p>
        <h5 class={h5}>Safe, IATA-compliant nationwide shipping</h5>
        <p class={p}>Our birds travel on IATA-compliant Delta, United or American flights — $185 to your nearest airport or $350 home delivery — crated, monitored and documented the whole way, so a verifiable breeder a few states away is still the right choice.</p>
        <h6 class={h6} style="color:#b04228">Breeder note: buyers who came to us torn between the two</h6>
        <p class={p}>Plenty of our owners arrived undecided between a Grey and an Eclectus. The ones who wanted conversation and a bird that engages with the whole family almost always landed on the Grey — and told us later that the daily "talking back" was exactly what they'd hoped for and what tipped the decision.</p>

        <BreederNote>
          <p>If you remember one line from this page, make it this: don't ask which bird is better, ask which bird fits the life you actually live. An African Grey in a home ready for its mind, or an Eclectus in a home ready for its diet, are both a joy for decades. The mismatch — either bird in the wrong home — is the only real wrong answer.</p>
        </BreederNote>

